{"term":"1981","caseName":"Federal Election Commission v. Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1981/80-939","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 06, 1981","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger8/oral_argument_audio/18864","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in Federal Election Commission against the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee and the consolidated case.","start":0,"stop":11.974,"duration":11.97},{"text":"Mr. Steele, you may proceed whenever you're ready.","start":11.974,"stop":14.843,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court, this case involves the expenditures provided in the Federal Election Campaign Act for political party committees made in connection with the general election campaigns of candidates of that political party.","start":14.843,"stop":33.721,"duration":18.88},{"text":"The amount awarded by the statute, allotted by the statute, is two cents per voter; technically, two cents per voter age population, which is the amount that the statute sets for the expenditures.","start":33.721,"stop":48.664,"duration":14.94},{"text":"The case arose before the Federal Election Commission on a complaint filed by the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.","start":48.664,"stop":56.503,"duration":7.84},{"text":"That complaint challenged the practice of the National Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee and the state party committees of the Republican Party, in which they agreed that the state party committee's allocation under the statute would be expended by the National Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee.","start":56.503,"stop":77.166,"duration":20.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Steele, only on behalf of the candidate in that state?","start":77.166,"stop":80.284,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and the statute makes that very clear, as I think the statutory history will show.","start":80.284,"stop":85.086,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":85.086,"stop":85.52,"duration":0.43},{"text":"That differs from the transfer provision, doesn't it?","start":85.52,"stop":89.14,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"The transfer of authority in this case was from the state parties in the individual states of the spending limit of two cents per voter that they would otherwise have for the candidates for the Senate in their state.","start":89.14,"stop":102.632,"duration":13.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In that state.","start":102.632,"stop":103.365,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"In that state, yes.","start":103.365,"stop":107.269,"duration":3.9},{"text":"The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee sought the Commission's reversal of an earlier decision for a similar practice in 1978.","start":107.269,"stop":119.076,"duration":11.81},{"text":"Complaint before the Commission explicitly asked that that decision be overruled; that the Commission seek injunctions and civil penalties against the practice of the National Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee.","start":119.076,"stop":135.169,"duration":16.09},{"text":"The Commission on July 11, 1980 found no reason to believe that that allegation stated a violation of the act and refused to take action on the complaint.","start":135.169,"stop":149.946,"duration":14.78},{"text":"The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee sought review as the statute provides in the District Court for the District of Columbia under the statutory provision 437g(a)(8), which provides that the District Court may review the Commission's action on a complaint and determine whether it was contrary to law.","start":149.946,"stop":171.961,"duration":22.02},{"text":"The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee appealed that decision to the Court of Appeals; the Court of Appeals reversed the decision of the District Court, finding that the statute's manifest purpose banned the practice of these agreements, found that the basis on which the Commission in earlier decisions had established this rule presented a shifting basis, gave no deference to the Commission's interpretation of the statute and ordered that the Commission proceed forthwith under the enforcement responsibilities in the statute, which DSCC had invoked by its complaint.","start":171.961,"stop":211.686,"duration":39.72},{"text":"Those enforcement responsibilities are set forth in our brief and I don't intend to go through them in great detail.","start":211.686,"stop":217.573,"duration":5.89},{"text":"They provide for complaints filed, notice to the opposite parties.","start":217.573,"stop":221.609,"duration":4.04},{"text":"If the Commission finds reason to believe, investigation, conciliation and eventual results would be that the Commission would find probable cause to believe.","start":221.609,"stop":230.667,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Steele, when you said that the Court of Appeals found that the Commission had shifted its position, would that be roughly analogous to the NLRB?","start":230.667,"stop":243.557,"duration":12.89}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that is analogous to the NLRB and other administrative law cases I think was the analogy that they were drawing on.","start":243.557,"stop":251.044,"duration":7.49},{"text":"We would submit that it is different here in that what the Commission is doing is exercising a prosecutorial authority rather than an adjudicatory authority such as the National Labor Relations Board Act.","start":251.044,"stop":263.471,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Hasn't this Court recognized the fact that the NLRB may, from time to time, shift its position, and either one may be right?","start":263.471,"stop":273.494,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly has, and I think the cases that we've cited reflect that.","start":273.494,"stop":277.629,"duration":4.13},{"text":"The Commission would submit that there was no shifting basis in its approach to these; that indeed, the very fact that the DSCC sought reversal of the decision in MUR 780, as it is noted in the Commission's records, is evidence of the fact that the Commission came to the same results in earlier cases.","start":277.629,"stop":296.275,"duration":18.65},{"text":"But I do think that in the cases that you cite, that even if there had been a shift, that that would still be within the discretionary authority of the Commission if it was rationalized and so forth and so on.","start":296.275,"stop":306.231,"duration":9.96},{"text":"But I do think this Court has recognized that... the ability of an administrative agency to re examine its position should not be foreclosed.","start":306.231,"stop":315.737,"duration":9.51},{"text":"The case raises issues both procedural and substantive in this case.","start":315.737,"stop":321.641,"duration":5.9},{"text":"Substantively, the question, which I will address in a moment, is whether the Commission was correct in its interpretation of the statute.","start":321.641,"stop":329.163,"duration":7.52},{"text":"I would like for a moment, however, to touch upon the procedural issue because I think the two are intertwined in such a way as to demonstrate the problem that the Commission has in the procedural aspects with the decision of the court below.","start":329.163,"stop":342.404,"duration":13.24},{"text":"The central issue in the case, in a sense, is whether the statute so clearly prohibits the sort of agreement that was entered into here; that it was unwarranted for the FEC not to prosecute the case, not to go forward under the provisions that it has for seeking enforcement of the act.","start":342.404,"stop":364.186,"duration":21.78},{"text":"The Court of Appeals stated that in its opinion, it was not a discretionary exercise of Commission power that was at issue here, but solely the interpretation of a statute.","start":364.186,"stop":376.727,"duration":12.54},{"text":"And it is precisely on that point that the Commission thinks that the court below erred; erred in relationship to other cases that it has decided with regard to the Federal Election Campaign Act in the Commission's exercise of its enforcement responsibilities, and erred more broadly in the overall context of administrative law.","start":376.727,"stop":394.939,"duration":18.21},{"text":"Indeed, as we have submitted in our brief, it would seem that the exercise of the prosecutorial power, the power to enforce the statute, is one that throughout the jurisprudence of this country has been seen as a discretionary one.","start":394.939,"stop":409.548,"duration":14.61},{"text":"What you have here is the decision by the Commission that it should not go forward in that mode.","start":409.548,"stop":415.618,"duration":6.07},{"text":"The decision of the Commission was based on a legal analysis; there was not a factual investigation here.","start":415.618,"stop":421.856,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Nonetheless, the decision of the court below suggests that the Commission must go forward.","start":421.856,"stop":428.343,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Now, as we have said in our brief, the Commission is structured in a way unlike many other commissions.","start":428.343,"stop":434.264,"duration":5.92},{"text":"It requires... it's a six member body, it requires the positive votes of four members to bring such an action.","start":434.264,"stop":442.852,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the vote here?","start":442.852,"stop":444.152,"duration":1.3},{"text":"Unanimous?","start":444.152,"stop":444.752,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"The vote here was unanimous.","start":444.752,"stop":445.554,"duration":0.8},{"text":"The vote in all three of the earlier decisions which we have referred to in our case, one advisory opinion back in 1976 and in the two enforcement cases in 1978, all of them were unanimous.","start":445.554,"stop":458.362,"duration":12.81},{"text":"They were all six nothing with the exception of one of the two MUR's where there were only five members present, but it was also unanimous.","start":458.362,"stop":467.551,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Those safeguards for the Commission's processes include, as I noted, the four votes required.","start":467.551,"stop":475.824,"duration":8.27},{"text":"There is, of course, the composition of the Commission.","start":475.824,"stop":478.293,"duration":2.47},{"text":"It is balanced so that there can be no vote of four members, by all the members of one party, as the statute prohibits the Commission from having more than three members of any one party.","start":478.293,"stop":494.135,"duration":15.84},{"text":"With regard to the merits, the Commission submits that its interpretation was not only reasonable, but was really quite consistent with the statute.","start":494.135,"stop":503.741,"duration":9.61},{"text":"I would emphasize, however, that it seems to the Commission that the standard that should be here applied is not whether its interpretation was the only one, but only whether its interpretation in light of the act, the words of the act, the context of the act, was a reasonable one.","start":503.741,"stop":522.286,"duration":18.54},{"text":"So, as far as the Commission is concerned, even if the statute is at least ambiguous it should prevail in this case, because the interpretation placed upon it by the court below that required the Commission to go forward was that the statutory mandate was clear.","start":522.286,"stop":541.366,"duration":19.08},{"text":"The review provision in 437g(8) provides that the Commission's actions will be reviewed to see if they are contrary to law.","start":541.366,"stop":549.353,"duration":7.99},{"text":"And the Commission concedes, as I think would be true even without that statute but with the statutory provision there, that obviously any dismissal of a complaint is reviewable by the courts.","start":549.353,"stop":559.411,"duration":10.06},{"text":"The Commission is not contesting that those decisions are not reviewable.","start":559.411,"stop":562.696,"duration":3.29},{"text":"The question is what the standard is that would be applied.","start":562.696,"stop":567.564,"duration":4.87},{"text":"In examining the merits, I would urge upon this Court to note, first of all, that the decision of the Commission and of the District Court in no way increased the limits that the statute provides for the spending in question.","start":567.564,"stop":581.741,"duration":14.18},{"text":"441a(d)(A)(3) provides that the national committee of a political party may send two cents per voter age population, and that the state committee may spend two cents per voter age population.","start":581.741,"stop":597.184,"duration":15.44},{"text":"That total, four cents for the party, has not been increased by the decision of the commission below.","start":597.184,"stop":604.607,"duration":7.42},{"text":"What the decision of the commission below said was, that the state party, which has a two cents per voter age population authority for spending under the statute, that the state party could assign that to the National Republican Senatorial Committee; that there was no bar in the statute to that action.","start":604.607,"stop":625.77,"duration":21.16},{"text":"The argument of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee accepted by the court below was that the statute, by providing separate limits for the national party and the state party, makes explicit that that limit must be spent by the national committee or must be spent by the state committee, and that there could be no transfer of it.","start":625.77,"stop":647.1,"duration":21.33},{"text":"Initially in 1976, when the Democratic National Committee filed a complaint and then withdrew it, there was an advisory opinion by the Commission.","start":647.1,"stop":657.871,"duration":10.77},{"text":"The Commission under 437f, 2 USC 437f, is authorized to issue advisory opinions to any person who requests them about specific transactions in which they are engaged.","start":657.871,"stop":670.529,"duration":12.66},{"text":"In that opinion, the Commission very clearly stated that in its view the National Republic Congressional Committee there, not the senatorial campaign committee.","start":670.529,"stop":680.735,"duration":10.21},{"text":"The two committees in question, one for the senatorial side, one for the congressional side, for the House side, are two separate committees.","start":680.735,"stop":688.472,"duration":7.74},{"text":"But for purposes of the statute, they are the same because they represent the same interests, one for the Senate side, one for the House side.","start":688.472,"stop":698.26,"duration":9.79},{"text":"The Commission's decision in AO 1976-108 explicitly stated that under its interpretation of the statute, referred to the legislative history of the 1976 amendments after this Court's decision in Buckley, that the National Republic Congressional Committee was a committee of the National Committee of the party.","start":698.26,"stop":718.072,"duration":19.81},{"text":"That is to say that it could be... the National Committee could assign to that committee its spending limits.","start":718.072,"stop":725.994,"duration":7.92},{"text":"That the National Republic Congressional Committee could spend its funds on a delegation from the Republic National Committee.","start":725.994,"stop":732.915,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Steele, may I ask, I noticed that the only thing argued below, I gather, was the validity of the agency agreements and not any validity of fund transfers.","start":732.915,"stop":742.705,"duration":9.79},{"text":"My question is this: could everything they attempted to do by agency agreements, they have done under 441a(a)(4) by transfer of funds if the congressional committees are not political committees within a(a)(4)?","start":742.705,"stop":758.049,"duration":15.34}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"They would be... the transfer provision would provide it to them as political committees of the same party.","start":758.049,"stop":764.136,"duration":6.09},{"text":"And we would argue certainly, the fact that they could transfer all the funds would allow them to do the identical matter that they did here.","start":764.136,"stop":770.023,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Then why all the fuss?","start":770.023,"stop":771.323,"duration":1.3},{"text":"What difference does it make?","start":771.323,"stop":772.992,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the decision of the court below was that there was loss of control; that here the state, by giving up its spending authority to the National Republican Senatorial Committee no longer retained control.","start":772.992,"stop":786.199,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And transferred the funds, if the prohibition of a(a)(4) doesn't apply to it, and if the state committee had transferred to the senatorial committee, apparently the same thing could have been accomplished, couldn't it?","start":786.199,"stop":797.507,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":797.507,"stop":797.89,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Or by our reasoning the same thing could have been accomplished by the National Republican Senatorial Committee, transferring the funds--","start":797.89,"stop":805.363,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Under agency agreement.","start":805.363,"stop":806.596,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":806.596,"stop":807.08,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my question is really, why do we have to fuss over the agency agreement if they could do it under a(a)(4) under the transfer provision?","start":807.08,"stop":814.569,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that you do, and indeed, I think that's the case that the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee is trying to make.","start":814.569,"stop":822.039,"duration":7.47},{"text":"That there is a difference there, but we would see no difference there.","start":822.039,"stop":826.907,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"While you've been interrupted may I just ask, in your view is the National Republican Senatorial Committee, the committee that's a party to this case, a, quote,","start":826.907,"stop":837.299,"duration":10.39},{"text":"\"national committee of a political party. \"","start":837.299,"stop":839.199,"duration":1.9},{"text":"within the meaning of 441a(d)(3)?","start":839.199,"stop":842.167,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is.","start":842.167,"stop":843.368,"duration":1.2},{"text":"And I would cite the decision that I was just mentioning, AO 1976-108, in which the Commission explicitly stated that on the basis of legislative history from the 76 amendments.","start":843.368,"stop":854.158,"duration":10.79},{"text":"That's cited at... I'm sorry, I don't have the page in our brief, but it's listed in our table on pages 25 and 29, and the Commission there explicitly held that.","start":854.158,"stop":866.318,"duration":12.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If that's correct, then again, the case is all over, isn't it?","start":866.318,"stop":872.222,"duration":5.9},{"text":"Because they have not spent more than that section permits them to spend, is that correct?","start":872.222,"stop":877.19,"duration":4.97},{"text":"I don't quite understand why we have to even get into the transfer of spending authority.","start":877.19,"stop":882.078,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't see why you do, either.","start":882.078,"stop":884.695,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Again, I think that that is our case, and I think you're stating it for me.","start":884.695,"stop":887.814,"duration":3.12},{"text":"The argument on the other side, I believe, is that by aggregating these two... the statute 441a(d)(3) provides a two cents for the national committee and a two cents for a state party committee, and that somehow the statute by providing those separate limits, which we agree that that allows the state committee not to transfer that to the national, so that the state committee has the authority to retain that spending power if it wishes, and that there's nothing in the statute... there's no mention in the statute of any prohibition of any arrangement like this, that at the very best the court below had to rely on the inference that by stating the two separate limits, that it meant that there should be no transfer.","start":887.814,"stop":927.189,"duration":39.38},{"text":"The court below also stated that its belief that the purpose of the statute was to strengthen the state parties... again, even conceding that that's so, which I don't think there's much citation of legislative history to support that, it would seem to us that the statute under the Commission's interpretation allows that.","start":927.189,"stop":946.52,"duration":19.33},{"text":"It allows the state, if it wishes to, to retain that spending authority.","start":946.52,"stop":950.822,"duration":4.3},{"text":"To turn for just a moment to the Court of Appeals decision below with regard to the question as to the shifting basis, not only would we contend, as I said in response to Justice Rehnquist's question, that even had there been a shift here that it enabled the agency to make that kind of decision and that's one of the purposes of having this kind of process.","start":950.822,"stop":974.42,"duration":23.6},{"text":"But we would submit that throughout all three of those decisions, the basic elements which I have set forth in discussing the merits, were there stated.","start":974.42,"stop":984.026,"duration":9.61},{"text":"The basic authority that the Commission relied on in all of them, including AO 1976-108, was the transfer authority.","start":984.026,"stop":991.882,"duration":7.86},{"text":"The court said that in some of the earlier MUR's the emphasis was on that and on the failure of the statute to explicitly prohibit this kind of transfer, and said that later decisions of the Commission suggested a shifting basis in that we then noted in this MUR in particular that later developments, that the Congress had legislation specifically in front of it... the House of Representatives had legislation specifically in front of it which would have prohibited the transfers proposed by the House Administration Committee.","start":991.882,"stop":1023.686,"duration":31.8},{"text":"There was a rule against that bill going forward, and we set forth in the decision in this case, the administrative decision in this case, MUR 1234 sets forth six or seven quotations from various congressmen, Congressmen Frenzel, Stockman, Conable, Mikva, Davis, both sides of the aisle, that the very purpose of that bill, the reason that they were speaking against it, of the rule to report the bill out, was because it was going to prohibit these kind of transfers.","start":1023.686,"stop":1048.968,"duration":25.28},{"text":"And on that basis we would think that the Commission's decision is not only reasonable but is in accord with the legislative history.","start":1048.968,"stop":1055.622,"duration":6.65},{"text":"I would reserve any further comment.","start":1055.622,"stop":1058.824,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":1058.824,"stop":1060.457,"duration":1.63},{"text":"Mr. Baran?","start":1060.457,"stop":1068.096,"duration":7.64}]},{"speakerName":"Jan W. Baran","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court, petitioner, National Republican Senatorial Committee, a committee of the Republican Party, seeks reversal of the Court of Appeals decision, just as the Federal Election Commission does.","start":1068.096,"stop":1082.487,"duration":14.39},{"text":"Our essential reason, set forth in our brief, is that the statute in question, which I'll refer to as Subsection (d)(3), simply does not prohibit the conduct that the Democratic Committee is complaining of.","start":1082.487,"stop":1096.663,"duration":14.18},{"text":"The limits, as Mr. Steele has indicated, have not been exceeded with respect to the total dollar amount, and it was noted so by Judge Wilke in his dissent, as well.","start":1096.663,"stop":1108.737,"duration":12.07},{"text":"What is being complained of is a method utilized within the political party for most effectively spending the money on behalf of senatorial candidates.","start":1108.737,"stop":1118.945,"duration":10.21},{"text":"And that method, which has been used by the Republican Party in 1978 and in 1980 on occasion and only voluntarily, is for the state committees of the Republican Party to designated the petitioner, NRSC, as an agent for purposes of spending funds on behalf of these candidates.","start":1118.945,"stop":1141.708,"duration":22.76},{"text":"The respondent has never in the course of the administrative proceeding or before any of the courts below suggested that the total amount of money spent for any specific Senate candidate in any state has been exceeded by the Republican Party.","start":1141.708,"stop":1159.004,"duration":17.3},{"text":"Unlike the Federal Election Commission, we do address the potential, although we feel unnecessary to reach, constitutional issues that would arise if the Court of Appeals decision were upheld.","start":1159.004,"stop":1173.929,"duration":14.93},{"text":"As Judge Wilke noted in his dissent, the interpretation that has been engrafted on this statute by the Court of Appeals would place a restriction in the way of the political party in terms of most effectively supporting its Senate candidates, even though it would be within the statutory limitation.","start":1173.929,"stop":1193.66,"duration":19.73},{"text":"Unlike the compelling governmental interest that has been recognized by this Court in Buckley v. Valeo, which is the prevention of corruption and the appearance of corruption, that interest is not advanced in furtherance of any such restriction.","start":1193.66,"stop":1210.039,"duration":16.38},{"text":"The respondent in their briefs suggest solely a government interest in revitalizing the state committees of the political parties.","start":1210.039,"stop":1220.894,"duration":10.86},{"text":"The Republican Party is certainly touched by this outpouring of concern on the part of the Democratic Committee for the well being of Republican state committees.","start":1220.894,"stop":1232.1,"duration":11.21},{"text":"It certainly is unprecedented, to say the least.","start":1232.1,"stop":1235.285,"duration":3.19},{"text":"But in terms of actual purpose behind Subsection (d)(3), there is no reflection in the legislative history, as we note in our brief, that there was any intention on the part of Congress when they passed Subsection (d)(3) back in 1974 to limit its benefits solely and narrowly to the state committee.","start":1235.285,"stop":1258,"duration":22.71},{"text":"The Congress was concerned with providing a still substantial role in private financing for political parties generally, but certainly not just for the state committees.","start":1258,"stop":1269.208,"duration":11.21},{"text":"And furthermore, as noted earlier by Mr. Steele, there are provisions within the statute itself that would indicate that Congress views the parties as basically one large entity and one large organization within the United States for financing purposes, to the point where unlike virtually any other component of campaign financing, any of the committees of the same party can shift unlimited funds back and forth to each other; implicitly recognizing that it's up to the political parties to make a decision on how to best structure their campaign financing within the overall limitations contained in the act.","start":1269.208,"stop":1312.57,"duration":43.36},{"text":"For those reasons, as set forth in greater detail in our brief, the petitioner NRSC requests reversal of the Court of Appeals decision.","start":1312.57,"stop":1322.093,"duration":9.52},{"text":"If there are no questions, I will conclude my argument.","start":1322.093,"stop":1325.045,"duration":2.95},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1325.045,"stop":1328.414,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer?","start":1328.414,"stop":1335.234,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court, what is striking about the last few minutes of argumentation offered by the FEC and the NRSC is that in construing the plain language of the provision in question, what Mr. Baran referred to as (d)(3), neither side offered any analysis of the plain terms of that provision.","start":1335.234,"stop":1359.182,"duration":23.95},{"text":"That is until Justice Stevens asked general counsel Steele whether NRSC was a national committee within the meaning of that section.","start":1359.182,"stop":1369.871,"duration":10.69},{"text":"General counsel Steele responded that it was, which is a mis analysis of the plain terms of the provision which lies at the heart of the agency's difficulty from the beginning of this case.","start":1369.871,"stop":1381.512,"duration":11.64},{"text":"The terms in Section (d)(3), Subsection (d)(3), are not ambiguous.","start":1381.512,"stop":1386.266,"duration":4.75},{"text":"They are separately defined in the definitions provision of the FECA.","start":1386.266,"stop":1392.32,"duration":6.05},{"text":"The definition about which Justice Stevens inquired, the national committee, is defined under Section 431(14) of the FECA as the organization... that is, one organization... which by virtue of the bylaws of a political party is responsible for the day to day operation of such political party at the national level.","start":1392.32,"stop":1417.436,"duration":25.12},{"text":"The NRSC is decidedly not the national committee of a political party, It is a sub unit of the national party structure, but the Commission itself has recognize that it is the Republican National Committee, which is not a party to this case, which is the national committee under Subsection (d)(3).","start":1417.436,"stop":1435.063,"duration":17.63},{"text":"More to the point is the analysis of what state committees are.","start":1435.063,"stop":1440.781,"duration":5.72},{"text":"Once again, Congress separately defines state committees in the definitions provision of the act, and it is concededly... in fact, conceded by all the parties to this litigation... that NRSC is not a state committee.","start":1440.781,"stop":1453.691,"duration":12.91},{"text":"How is it, then, that the agency has construed this provision, which confers defined limits on specifically defined entities, to allow NRSC not named or referred to in that provision to rest unto itself the limit that Congress has assigned to another?","start":1453.691,"stop":1473.688,"duration":20},{"text":"One of the problems in this case has been the agency's inability over a course of decisionmaking to offer a single consistent rationale for overcoming the plain terms of this provision.","start":1473.688,"stop":1485.496,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer, before you get too far along, it would be very helpful to me if you identified the language in the statute that prohibits what the NRSC has done.","start":1485.496,"stop":1495.352,"duration":9.86},{"text":"Because if they're not a national committee within the meaning of 441(a)(d)(3), I take it 441(a)(d)(3) just simply doesn't apply to NRSC.","start":1495.352,"stop":1504.29,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is absolutely correct, Justice Stevens, with one exception I should note here.","start":1504.29,"stop":1510.194,"duration":5.9},{"text":"And that is that in 1976, the Federal Election Commission promulgated a regulation following oral comment, hearings and submission to Congress subject to the one House veto provision, which purported to allow the national committee, under Subsection (d)(3), to assign its spending rights to any agent.","start":1510.194,"stop":1532.977,"duration":22.78},{"text":"This was the sole exception, as the FEC interpreted it at that time, and as Congress approved it at that time, to the defined limits and defined committees of Subsection (d)(3).","start":1532.977,"stop":1544.165,"duration":11.19},{"text":"In this litigation, however, for the first time before the Court of Appeals the FEC disavowed its prior interpretation of this regulation and now claims that it has no bearing whatsoever to Subsection (d)(3), but instead applies only to Subsection (d)(2) involving presidential elections.","start":1544.165,"stop":1563.079,"duration":18.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer, following up on Justice Stevens' question, where is the prohibitory language about which he asked?","start":1563.079,"stop":1570.816,"duration":7.74},{"text":"I've got open the Brief of the FEC at pages 2 and 3, which purportedly set forth the statutes involved.","start":1570.816,"stop":1582.307,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Rehnquist, Congress--","start":1582.307,"stop":1586.777,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"For the prohibitory language--","start":1586.777,"stop":1589.31,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--There is no language which prohibits assignments by name.","start":1589.31,"stop":1595.448,"duration":6.14},{"text":"However, the construction of the provision itself and an analysis of the relationship to that provision of other provisions to the act, suggest a conclusion very contrary to that suggested here by Mr. Baran.","start":1595.448,"stop":1607.441,"duration":11.99},{"text":"Party committee limits are not fungibled.","start":1607.441,"stop":1610.393,"duration":2.95},{"text":"They are not assignable, unless Congress expressly so state.","start":1610.393,"stop":1614.011,"duration":3.62},{"text":"And in some instances... and this, it seems to us, answers the argument fully... in some instances, Congress has provided precisely and specifically for the assignment of limits by one party committee to another, but it has been explicit where it has done so, and it has not done so in Subsection (d)(3).","start":1614.011,"stop":1631.639,"duration":17.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--So your reasoning is basically expressio unius est exclusio alterius.","start":1631.639,"stop":1636.591,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Justice Rehnquist.","start":1636.591,"stop":1638.376,"duration":1.79},{"text":"It also draws strength from the point that I just suggested to you, and that is that where Congress did intend party committee limits to be assignable, it expressly stated so.","start":1638.376,"stop":1649.268,"duration":10.89},{"text":"In Subsection (d)(3), for example, Congress expressly authorizes state committees to assign their limits altogether to, or to share them with, subordinate committees of the state party.","start":1649.268,"stop":1660.057,"duration":10.79},{"text":"Similarly, NRSC, as a congressional committee, possesses a $17,500 contribution limitation, which it is expressly authorized, again by the FECA, to share with the national committee of a political party, of its party.","start":1660.057,"stop":1674.133,"duration":14.08},{"text":"So Congress was very clear that if limits were to be assigned, it wished to have the final say so in the matter, and it did not provide for this assignment authority in Subsection (d)(3).","start":1674.133,"stop":1685.524,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer, What about a(a)(4)?","start":1685.524,"stop":1688.559,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"a(a)(4) also does not have the effect, it decidedly does not have the effect, of rendering the limits themselves, the integrity of the limits, for party committees and nullity.","start":1688.559,"stop":1701.384,"duration":12.83},{"text":"It is essentially the position of the FEC that because party committees can transfer funds freely among themselves, then the limits that Congress has given specific party committees should be disregarded.","start":1701.384,"stop":1713.258,"duration":11.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But if the congressional committees do not fall within the prohibition of 431a(a)(4), why can't they clearly exchange with the state committees?","start":1713.258,"stop":1725.684,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"They absolutely can exchange funds freely with the state committees, Justice Brennan.","start":1725.684,"stop":1728.886,"duration":3.2},{"text":"What they cannot do... they can exchange money.","start":1728.886,"stop":1731.422,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Money may be freely traded.","start":1731.422,"stop":1733.005,"duration":1.58},{"text":"What cannot be freely traded or assigned is the spending authority itself, which Congress made specific to different party committees.","start":1733.005,"stop":1742.461,"duration":9.46},{"text":"Money may pass freely, but congressionally assigned spending rights may not.","start":1742.461,"stop":1746.579,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What may they do with the money?","start":1746.579,"stop":1748.181,"duration":1.6},{"text":"They may transfer it freely.","start":1748.181,"stop":1749.631,"duration":1.45},{"text":"What may they do with it?","start":1749.631,"stop":1750.8,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"They might use it for Subsection (d)(3) purposes, (d)(2) purposes; they may use it for contribution limitations, they might use it to fund their administrative expenses.","start":1750.8,"stop":1760.155,"duration":9.36},{"text":"In fact, the legislative history which is in the record of this case suggests that when Congress crafted the transfer provision, all that it really had in mind was sort of a general facilitation of intra party cooperation, and Senator Hatfield referred, for example, specifically to the possibility that one committee could help another extinguish its debts.","start":1760.155,"stop":1779.033,"duration":18.88},{"text":"But there is no--","start":1779.033,"stop":1779.917,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it that they may not do?","start":1779.917,"stop":1784.219,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--The transfer provision is, in two instances which directly bear on this case, barred, or at least its use is barred.","start":1784.219,"stop":1794.677,"duration":10.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that?","start":1794.677,"stop":1797.16,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Federal Election Commission regulations at Section 100.7.","start":1797.16,"stop":1804.448,"duration":7.29},{"text":"In those--","start":1804.448,"stop":1805.248,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you saying that the Commission ignored its own regulations?","start":1805.248,"stop":1808.984,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, in this particular instance the use of the transfer provision is barred where state party committees are engaging in certain activities which are not involved in (d)(2).","start":1808.984,"stop":1820.642,"duration":11.66},{"text":"But I was responding to Justice Brennan's question about whether there is ever any explicit bar on transfers for a particular purpose, and there is.","start":1820.642,"stop":1828.564,"duration":7.92},{"text":"In the--","start":1828.564,"stop":1828.997,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact, by regulation, you suggest?","start":1828.997,"stop":1830.414,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--It is by regulation, the Commission having drawn upon language in the legislative history of those provisions.","start":1830.414,"stop":1836.134,"duration":5.72},{"text":"Congress had provided--","start":1836.134,"stop":1837.42,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And what is that bar?","start":1837.42,"stop":1839.436,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--The bar is that if the state party committees are to spend for certain special purposes--","start":1839.436,"stop":1843.738,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They being?","start":1843.738,"stop":1844.804,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--They being unlimited, get out the vote and voter registration expenses in presidential campaigns, and so called volunteer activities, where they can purchase without limit bumper stickers, buttons, yard signs, which volunteers may use.","start":1844.804,"stop":1859.398,"duration":14.59},{"text":"In those cases, the state committees alone have that spending authority and they may not accept funds for that purpose from the national committee of their party.","start":1859.398,"stop":1869.087,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's by regulation.","start":1869.087,"stop":1870.02,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is by Commission regulation drawing upon language in the legislative history.","start":1870.02,"stop":1873.539,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And this is the only regulation that--","start":1873.539,"stop":1874.741,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the only regulation on this point.","start":1874.741,"stop":1876.191,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Where do we find that in the briefs?","start":1876.191,"stop":1878.86,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be found in our brief, Your Honor, and I can--","start":1878.86,"stop":1885.346,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather this whole issue was not canvassed by the Court of Appeals, as I read its opinion.","start":1885.346,"stop":1890.683,"duration":5.34},{"text":"Am I right?","start":1890.683,"stop":1891.267,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--The Court of Appeals did draw upon the provisions in question.","start":1891.267,"stop":1894.469,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Except that it says, the parties have not argued the validity of funds transfers.","start":1894.469,"stop":1898.689,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, not under Section (d)(2).","start":1898.689,"stop":1900.289,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But only of agency agreements.","start":1900.289,"stop":1901.141,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, under--","start":1901.141,"stop":1902.974,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what we're talking about now was not considered by the Court of Appeals.","start":1902.974,"stop":1906.276,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--What we're talking about now was only considered by the Court of Appeals for one point which is critical here.","start":1906.276,"stop":1911.747,"duration":5.47},{"text":"And that is that Congress has been continually concerned that state party committees have a financial lever with which they can maintain their position in the electoral process.","start":1911.747,"stop":1921.804,"duration":10.06},{"text":"They have provided for an array of special spending provisions which state party committees and only those committees may use.","start":1921.804,"stop":1928.874,"duration":7.07},{"text":"And the purpose in those provisions as in Subsection (d)(2) is to guarantee the position of these parties in an age of national fund raising power and expensive media power.","start":1928.874,"stop":1938.397,"duration":9.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I interrupted you and you were going to tell us where that regulation was.","start":1938.397,"stop":1941.932,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Where in your brief is it?","start":1941.932,"stop":1946.103,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"In our brief, Your Honor, it is cited--","start":1946.103,"stop":1951.574,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it set forth?","start":1951.574,"stop":1953.374,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh, it is set forth in great detail.","start":1953.374,"stop":1955.276,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Where?","start":1955.276,"stop":1963.714,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"It is set forth in the material on the legislative history, which appears beginning page 23 and concludes on page 30, and the provisions that I am discussing appear at pages 28 through 30.","start":1963.714,"stop":1981.676,"duration":17.96},{"text":"The same provisions that I have discussed in response to yourself and Justice Brennan.","start":1981.676,"stop":1987.83,"duration":6.15},{"text":"And in those provisions, there is manifested broadly this congressional concern that state party committees have discrete and integral limits which cannot be freely traded away in contravention of congressional purposes.","start":1987.83,"stop":2003.34,"duration":15.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer, I really need more help from you.","start":2003.34,"stop":2007.743,"duration":4.4},{"text":"You've taken us into the regulations, and I'd like to stick with the statute, if I could, for a little bit.","start":2007.743,"stop":2013.212,"duration":5.47},{"text":"And it would help me if you could explain to me where... assuming that the NRSC is not a national committee within the meaning of 441a(3), where in the statute is there a prohibition against NRSC expending money?","start":2013.212,"stop":2030.24,"duration":17.03}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no prohibition, certainly, on NRSC expending money, Justice Stevens.","start":2030.24,"stop":2035.644,"duration":5.4},{"text":"In fact, NRSC has in Section 441a(h) a discrete contribution limitation which it shares with the national committee of $17,500.","start":2035.644,"stop":2046.201,"duration":10.56},{"text":"So it has never been the position of the respondent in this case that NRSC is barred from spending funds.","start":2046.201,"stop":2051.57,"duration":5.37},{"text":"Nor has it been our--","start":2051.57,"stop":2052.472,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What has it done that's illegal, other than spend funds?","start":2052.472,"stop":2055.391,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--It has assumed the congressional... the spending authority assigned--","start":2055.391,"stop":2058.759,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought it didn't need a spending authority; if there's no bar on its spending funds, how did it violate the statute?","start":2058.759,"stop":2064.013,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--The statute, Your Honor, provides generally for all committees, party and non party, that where funds are spent in support of a clearly identified candidate in cooperation with that candidate, the amounts that can be spent are limited.","start":2064.013,"stop":2081.959,"duration":17.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And what is it that limits the amount that can be spent by NRSC?","start":2081.959,"stop":2086.493,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"NRSC as other committees, as other party committees are, is subject to specific spending limits in the--","start":2086.493,"stop":2093.266,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it, and in what section of the statute may I find it?","start":2093.266,"stop":2096.218,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--You may find it in Section 441a(h), where that and the other congressional campaign committees are cited by name.","start":2096.218,"stop":2104.372,"duration":8.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that section quoted in the briefs?","start":2104.372,"stop":2107.859,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is, Justice Stevens.","start":2107.859,"stop":2110.811,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"441a(h)--","start":2110.811,"stop":2113.178,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, 441a(h).","start":2113.178,"stop":2122.867,"duration":9.69},{"text":"The question of whether Congress intended political committees of a party to have discrete limits--","start":2122.867,"stop":2129.204,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--I hate to do this, but which brief at which page, do you know?","start":2129.204,"stop":2132.99,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--I suspect in all the briefs, Justice Stevens, but in our brief it is cited at pages 26 and 37.","start":2132.99,"stop":2147.399,"duration":14.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it quoted anywhere?","start":2147.399,"stop":2150.034,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not cited at length in any of the briefs, to my knowledge.","start":2150.034,"stop":2152.886,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not quoted, even \"that is the provision\" that you allege they violated?","start":2152.886,"stop":2157.088,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, our allegation has not been that they're violating 441a(h).","start":2157.088,"stop":2162.342,"duration":5.25},{"text":"Our--","start":2162.342,"stop":2163.109,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But if they didn't violate that, and that's the only statutory provision that prohibits them from spending money, how can they have violated the statute if they didn't violate that?","start":2163.109,"stop":2172.633,"duration":9.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Stevens, the problem lies in the history of this litigation.","start":2172.633,"stop":2176.418,"duration":3.79},{"text":"There used to be, until the FEC disavowed it, an additional source of spending by NRSC by regulation.","start":2176.418,"stop":2184.957,"duration":8.54},{"text":"In 1976, as I mentioned--","start":2184.957,"stop":2186.123,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I was hoping I could get the basic framework of the statute.","start":2186.123,"stop":2189.675,"duration":3.55},{"text":"You must rely on regulations to find a violation, I take it.","start":2189.675,"stop":2194.313,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, Your Honor, because absent that regulation by the Commission which provided NRSC with a separate, with a separate source of funding, and a considerably substantial one, absent that regulation it is absolutely correct that by receiving an assignment of funds from the state party committees... excuse me, receiving an assignment of authority from the state party committees, NRSC's expenditures did violate the act.","start":2194.313,"stop":2220.796,"duration":26.48},{"text":"It, in fact, violated 441a(h).","start":2220.796,"stop":2223.748,"duration":2.95},{"text":"Absent the regulation.","start":2223.748,"stop":2226.015,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they violate any section other than 441a(h)?","start":2226.015,"stop":2231.736,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, they did not.","start":2231.736,"stop":2238.473,"duration":6.74},{"text":"The question of whether or not party committee limits have been deemed by Congress to be specific can be answered by reference to the legislative history of Subsection (d)(2).","start":2238.473,"stop":2248.679,"duration":10.21},{"text":"That provision, leaving aside its plain terms which do not refer to NRSC, was enacted in 1974, and the legislative history shows that Congress was well aware of the congressional committees in 1974.","start":2248.679,"stop":2264.271,"duration":15.59},{"text":"In fact, there was pending on the floor of the Senate at that time a proposal to exempt the congressional committees altogether from spending limits, and that proposal was rejected.","start":2264.271,"stop":2276.912,"duration":12.64},{"text":"In 1976, the question of NRSC spending authority was raised yet again, and this time it was raised through a $17,500 contribution limit, which it shares with the national committee of its party.","start":2276.912,"stop":2292.755,"duration":15.84},{"text":"But not at that time nor in the years before did Congress elect to confer upon NRSC a share in the state committee's spending authority under Subsection (d)(3).","start":2292.755,"stop":2304.396,"duration":11.64},{"text":"It was a considered question by Congress, and Congress addressed it forthrightly.","start":2304.396,"stop":2309.716,"duration":5.32},{"text":"Similarly, the transfer provision is no answer.","start":2309.716,"stop":2313.418,"duration":3.7},{"text":"While it is true that funds can be transferred freely between committees, it is also clear from the scheme of the act and its legislative history that party committee limits are not fungible.","start":2313.418,"stop":2325.31,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Unless Congress has expressly stated that those limits are to be shared or assigned, and it has in the provisions I cited to Justice Rehnquist, assignability is barred.","start":2325.31,"stop":2335.95,"duration":10.64},{"text":"In the last analysis, the FEC and NRSC in this case have shrugged their shoulders and said what difference does it make; form over substance.","start":2335.95,"stop":2346.473,"duration":10.52},{"text":"It doesn't matter whether the state committees spend the funds or whether NRSC does.","start":2346.473,"stop":2351.893,"duration":5.42},{"text":"Respondent submits that the question of form or substance in matters of policy are not for the agency to make.","start":2351.893,"stop":2360.416,"duration":8.52},{"text":"It is for Congress to make policy judgments in the election scheme.","start":2360.416,"stop":2365.22,"duration":4.8},{"text":"In any event, the question of form which is before this Court, is decidedly one of substance.","start":2365.22,"stop":2371.457,"duration":6.24},{"text":"For in this Subsection (d)(3), as in other provisions of the act which I've cited in the colloquy with Justice Rehnquist, Congress made specific provision for special spending rights by state committees and their subordinate units, and it did so because of a very strongly expressed concern that these committees would not be in a position to maintain their role absent this special provisions of Congress.","start":2371.457,"stop":2396.906,"duration":25.45},{"text":"The record in this case shows that the congressional concern was by no means unfounded, for uncontroverted in that record is evidence that in 1978 when these state committee NSRC authority assignments were first made, state party committees spent virtually no money under the authority provided under Subsection (d)(3).","start":2396.906,"stop":2421.323,"duration":24.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was their own choice, wasn't it?","start":2421.323,"stop":2423.173,"duration":1.85},{"text":"I mean, they're not compelled to make their assignment to the national senatorial committee.","start":2423.173,"stop":2429.579,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Justice Rehnquist.","start":2429.579,"stop":2431.345,"duration":1.77},{"text":"At the same time, Congress did not foreclose from holding out an incentive to these entities to try to maintain their own place.","start":2431.345,"stop":2438.435,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And certainly, the availability of this assignment authority only makes it easier for state committees to essentially abdicate the role.","start":2438.435,"stop":2446.089,"duration":7.65},{"text":"It is far easier for a national fund raising base like NRSC to raise the money for congressional elections across the country than for, say, the state committees of Missouri, Kentucky, Iowa and Alabama.","start":2446.089,"stop":2458.479,"duration":12.39},{"text":"Yet Congress held out to those committees that incentive to do so, to raise the money and then spend it in their own congressional elections, and the assignability of those limits completely contradicts this congressional purpose.","start":2458.479,"stop":2474.524,"duration":16.05},{"text":"So it is that the record shows that through this spending pattern, Section 441a(d)(3) has essentially been stood on its head.","start":2474.524,"stop":2482.88,"duration":8.36},{"text":"What was intended as an incentive to state and local party organizations has instead been turned into a supplement to national fund raising power.","start":2482.88,"stop":2491.736,"duration":8.86},{"text":"And as this court noted in Buckley, in an age of media politics, expensive polling techniques and other refined forms of campaigning, money, very expensive money, certainly talks.","start":2491.736,"stop":2505.043,"duration":13.31},{"text":"And without the special provision made for the state committees, the aggregation of power will be pulled further and further toward the national center of the country, which is a result Congress sought to avoid.","start":2505.043,"stop":2516.768,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer, would you just enumerate for me what are the limitations on state committee expenditures?","start":2516.768,"stop":2526.874,"duration":10.11}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Brennan, state committees may--","start":2526.874,"stop":2528.893,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They want to transfer agency or whatever you want to call it with the NRSC, but you say they can't.","start":2528.893,"stop":2536.765,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--They cannot transfer the spending authority.","start":2536.765,"stop":2539.65,"duration":2.89},{"text":"They may transfer funds for whatever purpose they choose to other party committees.","start":2539.65,"stop":2543.585,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't see what that means.","start":2543.585,"stop":2545.454,"duration":1.87},{"text":"If they've got $50,000, you're saying they can transfer the $50,000 but they can't transfer whatever the requirement is that they spend the $50,000, is that it?","start":2545.454,"stop":2555.16,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, and I think the significance--","start":2555.16,"stop":2556.593,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it that they have to spend the $50,000 on?","start":2556.593,"stop":2559.711,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, this is... that is probably the most significant point in our case, Justice Brennan, and it goes to what Justice Stevens asked me about NRSC's own spending limit.","start":2559.711,"stop":2569.751,"duration":10.04},{"text":"Let us assume for purposes here, without again addressing the FEC regulation, that NRSC is limited to $17,500 to a candidate.","start":2569.751,"stop":2580.291,"duration":10.54},{"text":"And let us assume that a state committee then transfer to NRSC $50,000.","start":2580.291,"stop":2585.41,"duration":5.12},{"text":"All that NRSC can do to influence the outcome of a specific candidate's election is spend $17,500.","start":2585.41,"stop":2592.766,"duration":7.36}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And what happens to the rest of the money?","start":2592.766,"stop":2594.116,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Presumably, NRSC makes some arrangement to spend it for some other purpose, but not in congressional elections, which is precisely why if the committee's limits were respected, the additional money that the committee would retain at the state and local level--","start":2594.116,"stop":2607.859,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, if the state committee had kept the $50,000, what may they do with it?","start":2607.859,"stop":2610.644,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--They may make a contribution to a candidate of $5000 per election; they may make expenditures equivalent to two cents multiplied by the voting age population of the state.","start":2610.644,"stop":2620.417,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But those are limitations on how much of the $50,000 they may spend on a particular candidate.","start":2620.417,"stop":2624.451,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's precisely correct, Justice Brennan.","start":2624.451,"stop":2627.353,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case, what do they propose to do with this money?","start":2627.353,"stop":2630.557,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"The NRSC took the transfers of authority from the state committees, thereby substantially increasing its own limit, and indeed--","start":2630.557,"stop":2639.747,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But has it distributed any money?","start":2639.747,"stop":2645.115,"duration":5.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--It has distributed millions under this transfer of authority to Senate candidates.","start":2645.115,"stop":2650.186,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They have used the authority and spent the money.","start":2650.186,"stop":2653.655,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2653.655,"stop":2654.221,"duration":0.57},{"text":"They have used state committee authority, and NRSC has spent the money, its money, for--","start":2654.221,"stop":2658.625,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say they can't do either.","start":2658.625,"stop":2660.493,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--It may receive the transfers, but it may not double its own limit with the limit of the state committees.","start":2660.493,"stop":2666.98,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me back up a little, Mr. Bauer.","start":2666.98,"stop":2669.599,"duration":2.62},{"text":"If you have addressed the question of the interpretation placed on this statute by the agency I missed it.","start":2669.599,"stop":2680.122,"duration":10.52},{"text":"Now certainly, of all the agencies created by Congress, I would assume that the people selected for this kind of a commission, which is unique, three from each party is that correct?","start":2680.122,"stop":2698.786,"duration":18.66}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, sir.","start":2698.786,"stop":2700.219,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would hardly be political neophytes.","start":2700.219,"stop":2704.003,"duration":3.78},{"text":"They'd be people who are very sophisticated politically, which might not necessarily be true of an appointee to the Federal Communications Commission or Federal Power Commission, who might or might not be sophisticated in the particular area.","start":2704.003,"stop":2718.513,"duration":14.51},{"text":"Now, what weight should be given by the Judiciary to the interpretation of the congressional mandate by this uniquely expert and sophisticated commission?","start":2718.513,"stop":2732.59,"duration":14.08},{"text":"Now, those are my objectives.","start":2732.59,"stop":2734.292,"duration":1.7},{"text":"You don't have to adopt them.","start":2734.292,"stop":2736.009,"duration":1.72},{"text":"What weight should be given?","start":2736.009,"stop":2738.327,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Chief Justice Burger, I think they should receive the substantial weight and the substantial deference that is ordinarily accorded, perhaps no more than that, to agencies that are charged with administering particular statutes.","start":2738.327,"stop":2750.384,"duration":12.06},{"text":"But this case really raises the threshold to something very different.","start":2750.384,"stop":2754.52,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And that is the question of whether an agency can disrespect the law.","start":2754.52,"stop":2758.472,"duration":3.95},{"text":"The plain terms of this provision, and the construction of the statute as a whole suggests that they are permitting the bandying about the assignment of authority which Congress intended to be specific to particular committees.","start":2758.472,"stop":2774.232,"duration":15.76},{"text":"Now, if there was room open under this provision for different interpretations of which committees may spend and which committees may not, respondent might not be here.","start":2774.232,"stop":2783.254,"duration":9.02},{"text":"But this provision could not be clearer.","start":2783.254,"stop":2785.956,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Congress selected particular terms and then went to great lengths to define them.","start":2785.956,"stop":2789.507,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it seemed clear just the other way to the six members of the Commission who passed on it initially, is that not so?","start":2789.507,"stop":2798.097,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":2798.097,"stop":2798.847,"duration":0.75},{"text":"But respondent submits, and as a committee subject to the continuing regulation of the Federal Election Commission it has a special stake in expressing its concern, that unanimity of opinion on that agency not be considered sufficient to overcome the plain terms of any provision.","start":2798.847,"stop":2814.107,"duration":15.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Even your own Democrats.","start":2814.107,"stop":2815.557,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Even our own Democrats, Justice Brennan.","start":2815.557,"stop":2818.926,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Honest differences of opinion, but on this case we happen to think we have the law on our side.","start":2818.926,"stop":2824.228,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bauer, can I go back to the statute again, because I think I'm beginning to understand your argument.","start":2824.228,"stop":2828.532,"duration":4.3},{"text":"0 [Generallaughter.]","start":2828.532,"stop":2829.865,"duration":1.33},{"text":"If I understand it, you're saying that Subsection (h) which places a limit on the contributions the National Republican Senatorial Committee can make to any state candidate is 1$7,500.","start":2829.865,"stop":2840.505,"duration":10.64},{"text":"And that when it spends more money than that in behalf of the candidate, it is, in effect, making an additional contribution to the candidate.","start":2840.505,"stop":2847.659,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is absolutely correct, Justice Stevens.","start":2847.659,"stop":2849.045,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And therefore, you've violated the prohibition against contributions in excess of this amount.","start":2849.045,"stop":2853.397,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"And I might emphasize to nail that point home, because I know you're eager for me to do so, that the act specifically defines Subsection (d)(2) expenditures as contributions.","start":2853.397,"stop":2863.871,"duration":10.47},{"text":"There has been much weight placed for constitutional purposes by NRSC on the identity of this spending as, quote, expenditures.","start":2863.871,"stop":2871.525,"duration":7.65},{"text":"But the statute itself defines coordinated expenditures, expenditures which are arranged with the candidate, as no different functionally than contributions.","start":2871.525,"stop":2882.832,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So your violation in this case that you rely on is the amount over $17,500 that they spend for any given candidate.","start":2882.832,"stop":2891.272,"duration":8.44},{"text":"Does the record tell us whether they did, in fact, spend more than $17,500?","start":2891.272,"stop":2895.324,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it does.","start":2895.324,"stop":2896.026,"duration":0.7},{"text":"The Joint Appendix of the Court of Appeals has notarized affidavits with substantial figures for each state.","start":2896.026,"stop":2902.93,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just amazed that nobody quoted Subsection (h) in their briefs.","start":2902.93,"stop":2906.532,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, one of the murkier moments in this litigation was, I fear, created by the Federal Election Commission because it used to be that--","start":2906.532,"stop":2915.638,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But one of the beauties of the adversary system is we don't have to rely on our adversary to quote the relevant statutory language.","start":2915.638,"stop":2920.59,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--That is correct.","start":2920.59,"stop":2921.14,"duration":0.55},{"text":"But the regulation which we relied on to suggest that maybe NRSC had a higher than $17,500 contribution limit, that regulation was in force until all of a sudden in this litigation the FEC changed its mind, said it didn't apply.","start":2921.14,"stop":2936.884,"duration":15.74},{"text":"So a regulation interpreted one way--","start":2936.884,"stop":2938.567,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How much higher than $17,500 was--","start":2938.567,"stop":2940.936,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"--It was the two cents per voting age population in each state as agent of the National Committee of the political party.","start":2940.936,"stop":2947.59,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--And that could amount to how much?","start":2947.59,"stop":2949.075,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Robert F. Bauer","textObjs":[{"text":"It could amount, under the figures in the Joint Appendix, to slightly in excess of three million dollars, nationally.","start":2949.075,"stop":2957.729,"duration":8.65},{"text":"So it was in light of that confusion over what precisely NRSC's spending authority was that I think all parties backed away from addressing themselves forthrightly to 441a(h) versus perhaps some other provision.","start":2957.729,"stop":2974.873,"duration":17.14},{"text":"While I do not believe that it merits excessive attention here, NRSC has offered yet another in a long string of interpretations to support the FEC's position.","start":2974.873,"stop":2987.248,"duration":12.38},{"text":"And that is a constitutional claim, which I do not think this Court need reach in light of the plain terms of the provision.","start":2987.248,"stop":2993.937,"duration":6.69},{"text":"The NRSC's claim has to be understood first of all as not a challenge to the constitutionality of any limitation on state party committee spending.","start":2993.937,"stop":3004.976,"duration":11.04},{"text":"None of the parties to this litigation are quarreling over whether Congress can constitutionally limit political party spending.","start":3004.976,"stop":3012.481,"duration":7.51},{"text":"The question instead is whether, within this overall scheme of limits, Congress may direct that certain committees can spend a certain amount and other committees a different amount for specific and well defined purposes.","start":3012.481,"stop":3028.241,"duration":15.76},{"text":"There is no evidence in the record certainly to support NRSC's contention that its First Amendment rights are impermissibly burdened by an agency proscription.","start":3028.241,"stop":3038.43,"duration":10.19},{"text":"Nor is it likely that that evidence could be developed.","start":3038.43,"stop":3042.482,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Political parties have exceptionally, exceptionally broad avenues of spending participation available to them under the act.","start":3042.482,"stop":3050.486,"duration":8},{"text":"Avenues which are not available to non party committees, and Subsection (d)(3) is one example.","start":3050.486,"stop":3056.622,"duration":6.14},{"text":"And whatever infringement may, in fact, result from proscribing these agency agreements and enforcing congressional will, they are certainly marginal when measured against the government's very compelling concern with maintaining the state and local political party role in the electoral process.","start":3056.622,"stop":3074.434,"duration":17.81},{"text":"That's a concern which, of course, is Federalist at heart.","start":3074.434,"stop":3077.453,"duration":3.02},{"text":"There is a substantial body of scholarly opinion supporting the view that this is absolutely necessary, and we would not be quarreling about it if the agency in this case had done what we urge this Court now to do, and that is affirm the Court of Appeals decision below, have Subsection (d)(3) construed as it was written, and thereby bring the agency back into conformity with the rule of law under this statutory scheme.","start":3077.453,"stop":3104.27,"duration":26.82}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have anything further, Mr. Steele?","start":3104.27,"stop":3109.107,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"With regard to the question of why 441a(h) was not set forth in the briefs, the fact is that the complaint that was lodged with the Comission alleged a violation of 441a(d)(3), and perhaps I might just refer, Justice Stevens, you to that section as seeming to set forth the prohibition that you were asking for.","start":3109.107,"stop":3132.873,"duration":23.77},{"text":"The beginning of that Section, a (d)(1), says,","start":3132.873,"stop":3137.193,"duration":4.32},{"text":"\"notwithstanding any other provision of law with respect to limitations on expenditures or limitations on contributions, the national committee of a political party and a state committee of a political party, including any subordinate committee, may make expenditures in connection with the general election campaign of candidates for federal office, subject to the limitations set forth. \"","start":3137.193,"stop":3158.107,"duration":20.91},{"text":"Those limitations are set forth in Subsections (2) and (3).","start":3158.107,"stop":3161.225,"duration":3.12},{"text":"(2) pertains to the presidential election.","start":3161.225,"stop":3164.361,"duration":3.14},{"text":"(3), which was what was put at issue before the Commission and before the courts, pertains to the congressional elections.","start":3164.361,"stop":3172.265,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":3172.265,"stop":3173.083,"duration":0.82},{"text":"But my problem all along has been, and I think Justice Rehnquist may have made a similar observation, that this is authorizing language, it's not prohibitory language, in (1), (2) and (3).","start":3173.083,"stop":3184.424,"duration":11.34},{"text":"And I have to start with a prohibition somewhere in the statute in order to find a violation.","start":3184.424,"stop":3190.078,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":3190.078,"stop":3191.044,"duration":0.97},{"text":"The prohibition--","start":3191.044,"stop":3192.261,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you not agree that what you've referred to is authorizing language.","start":3192.261,"stop":3196.732,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, it is.","start":3196.732,"stop":3197.832,"duration":1.1},{"text":"The prohibition language, in almost perhaps an inverted way, comes in Subsection (3) where it says,","start":3197.832,"stop":3206.088,"duration":8.26},{"text":"\"the national committee of a political party or a state committee of a political party, including any subordinate committee, may not make any expenditure in connection with the general election campaign of a candidate for federal office in a state who is affiliated with such party, which exceeds. \"","start":3206.088,"stop":3223.549,"duration":17.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":3223.549,"stop":3224.115,"duration":0.57},{"text":"But, of course, then the one issue is whether or not NRSC is, quote, \"The National Committee\", and your opponent says that's a term defined in the statute, and that this is not that particular committee.","start":3224.115,"stop":3235.607,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3235.607,"stop":3235.923,"duration":0.32},{"text":"And as we have said, it is not the national committee.","start":3235.923,"stop":3240.677,"duration":4.75},{"text":"What we have set forth in the brief and in the advisory opinion that I referred you to, is that there are subordinate committees of the national committee.","start":3240.677,"stop":3252.069,"duration":11.39},{"text":"Indeed, DSCC itself makes expenditures on behalf of the DNC, and that that delegation has never been questioned.","start":3252.069,"stop":3262.84,"duration":10.77},{"text":"That is the delegation explicitly set forth in 110.7 of our regulations.","start":3262.84,"stop":3267.661,"duration":4.82},{"text":"So that the delegation by the national committee of its spending authority to subordinate committees has been accepted by the Commission.","start":3267.661,"stop":3276.684,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me again just put to one side delegation questions.","start":3276.684,"stop":3280.319,"duration":3.63},{"text":"Did I correctly understand you in your opening argument to take the position that the National Republican Senatorial Committee is, quote, (d)(3)?","start":3280.319,"stop":3293.377,"duration":13.06}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a subordinate committee; it is not the national committee.","start":3293.377,"stop":3295.995,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not the national committee now.","start":3295.995,"stop":3299.031,"duration":3.04},{"text":"But is it a committee referred to in (d)(3)?","start":3299.031,"stop":3302.565,"duration":3.53},{"text":"There's no other language... oh, you say it is a subordinate committee of what?","start":3302.565,"stop":3309.236,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the national committee.","start":3309.236,"stop":3311.004,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But there is no reference to subordinate committee of the national committee in (d)(3), is there?","start":3311.004,"stop":3315.723,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":3315.723,"stop":3316.206,"duration":0.48},{"text":"That was the question posed to the Commission in AO 1976-108 where the Commission, again relying on the statutory history of the 1976, the conference report of the 1976 amendments, came to the conclusion it's the view of the Commission that the specified campaign committees are committees of their respective national political parties.","start":3316.206,"stop":3338.739,"duration":22.53},{"text":"And on that basis, seized them as being... we set forth in a footnote in our brief the various committees.","start":3338.739,"stop":3344.225,"duration":5.49},{"text":"So the Commission has viewed the national committee as having many subordinate committees.","start":3344.225,"stop":3349.546,"duration":5.32},{"text":"I apologize if my answer earlier misled you.","start":3349.546,"stop":3353.165,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm still, I must confess but I'll study it further, a little uncertain of your position on whether the statute itself in (d)(3) makes reference to the National Republican Senatorial Committee, which isn't mentioned by name in Subsection (h).","start":3353.165,"stop":3369.358,"duration":16.19}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that was a later enacted statute, I might note.","start":3369.358,"stop":3372.543,"duration":3.18},{"text":"That was passed in 1976, and a(d)(3) was passed in 1974.","start":3372.543,"stop":3376.197,"duration":3.65},{"text":"It is not specifically mentioned in a(d)(3).","start":3376.197,"stop":3379.749,"duration":3.55},{"text":"The Commission's position would be that it is... that NRSC and the DSCC are subordinates to the national--","start":3379.749,"stop":3386.552,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But that section also does not mention subordinate committees of the national committee.","start":3386.552,"stop":3391.956,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct.","start":3391.956,"stop":3393.073,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So what is the legal significance of classifying those committees as subordinate committees of the national committee?","start":3393.073,"stop":3401.396,"duration":8.32},{"text":"I really have lost the argument.","start":3401.396,"stop":3403.931,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"The significance of it is that they are all part of the same national committee, as far as the Commission is concerned.","start":3403.931,"stop":3408.835,"duration":4.9},{"text":"They are branches of the same--","start":3408.835,"stop":3410.852,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"You construe the statute as though it read the national committee of a political party or any subordinate committee of a national committee of a political party may--","start":3410.852,"stop":3418.274,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Charles Nevett Steele","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":3418.274,"stop":3418.874,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Which is not explicit in the statute.","start":3418.874,"stop":3419.674,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--I see.","start":3419.674,"stop":3425.126,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, gentlemen, the case is submitted.","start":3425.126,"stop":3426.842,"duration":1.72}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Oct 6, 1981","petitioner":"Federal Election Commission","respondent":"Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee","docket":"80-939","citation":"454 US 27 (1981)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/454/27","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Nov 10, 1981"}